  "prompt": "If India was a part of UNSC would it have been able to ban Masood Azhar without China's support?",
  "response": "In the context of the United Nations Security Council (UNSC), any substantive decision such as the imposition of sanctions or the designation of an individual as a terrorist requires the consensus or at least the non-opposition of all five permanent members (the P5: the United States, the United Kingdom, France, Russia, and China). Each of these countries has the power to veto any substantive resolution.\n\nIf India were to become a permanent member of the UNSC and attempted to organize the banning of Masood Azhar, it would still need the support or at least the non-opposition of the other permanent members. China's stance on such issues has historically been significant, as it has previously blocked attempts to designate Masood Azhar as a terrorist due to its relationship with Pakistan. Therefore, even if India were a part of the UNSC, achieving this goal would still require diplomatic efforts to secure China's or other members' agreement or neutrality on the matter.\n\nIn essence, while India's membership in the UNSC would increase its influence and ability to propose such actions, it would still necessitate the cooperation or acquiescence of other permanent members, including China, to successfully implement the ban.",
